\frame{\titlepage \thispagestyle{empty}}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Roadmap}
\begin{wideitemize}
\item Part A (catch-up): regression discontinuity (RD)
\item Part B: differences in differences (DiD) and panel-data designs (next)
\end{wideitemize}
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}[fragile]{Potential outcomes as functions of \(X\)}
\small
Think of the average potential outcomes as smooth regression functions:
\[
m_0(x)\equiv \E[Y_i(0)\mid X_i=x],\qquad
m_1(x)\equiv \E[Y_i(1)\mid X_i=x].
\]\pause
The (conditional) average treatment effect at a point \(x^\star\) is
\[
\tau(x^\star)\equiv \E[Y_i(1)-Y_i(0)\mid X_i=x^\star]=m_1(x^\star)-m_0(x^\star).
\]

<<potential-outcomes-picture, echo=FALSE, fig=TRUE, height=3.2, width=7.5>>=
  suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ggplot2))

  x <- seq(0, 10, length.out = 400)
  x_star <- 6

  m0 <- function(x) 0.45 * x + 1.2 * sin(x / 1.6) + 0.2
  tau_x <- function(x) 1.6 + 0.35 * sin((x - 1.5) / 1.3) + 0.08 * (x - 5)
  m1 <- function(x) m0(x) + tau_x(x)

  df <- rbind(
    data.frame(x = x, y = m0(x), curve = "m0(x) = E[Y(0) | X=x]"),
    data.frame(x = x, y = m1(x), curve = "m1(x) = E[Y(1) | X=x]")
  )

  df_tau <- data.frame(
    x = x_star,
    y0 = m0(x_star),
    y1 = m1(x_star),
    tau = m1(x_star) - m0(x_star)
  )

  ggplot(df, aes(x, y, color = curve)) +
    geom_line(linewidth = 0.8) +
    geom_vline(xintercept = x_star, linewidth = 0.4, color = "gray40") +
    geom_segment(
      data = df_tau,
      aes(x = x, xend = x, y = y0, yend = y1),
      inherit.aes = FALSE,
      linewidth = 0.8
    ) +
    annotate(
      "text",
      x = x_star + 0.15,
      y = (df_tau$y0 + df_tau$y1) / 2,
      label = sprintf("tau(x*) = %.2f", df_tau$tau),
      hjust = 0,
      size = 3.6
    ) +
    labs(x = "Covariate X", y = NULL) +
    theme_classic(base_size = 12) +
    theme(
      strip.background = element_blank(),
      strip.text.y = element_text(angle = 0, hjust = 0),
      plot.margin = margin(4, 4, 4, 4)
    ) + 
    scale_color_manual(values = c("m0(x) = E[Y(0) | X=x]" = "steelblue", 
                                  "m1(x) = E[Y(1) | X=x]" = "firebrick"))

@
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{RD setup (Imbens--Lemieux notation)}
\small
We observe \((Y_i, D_i, X_i)\), where \(X_i\) is the forcing variable and \(D_i\in\{0,1\}\) is treatment/receipt.\pause

\begin{wideitemize}
\item Cutoff: \(c\).\pause
\item Core comparison: units just below vs.\ just above \(c\) (\emph{local}).\pause
\item \textbf{Sharp RD (SRD):} \(D_i=\one\{X_i\ge c\}\).\pause
\item \textbf{Fuzzy RD (FRD):} \(\Pr[D_i=1\mid X_i=x]\) jumps at \(c\), but not from 0 to 1.\pause
\end{wideitemize}

\vspace{0.25em}
\pause
FRD is a local IV design: crossing the cutoff shifts treatment probability.

\vspace{0.25em}
\scriptsize
Many notes re-center the forcing variable so the cutoff is 0: define \(V_i\equiv X_i-c\). We mainly write \(X_i\) and \(c\).
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}[fragile]{Motivation pictures: assignment and regression functions}
\small
In SRD, the treatment probability jumps from 0 to 1 at the cutoff, so the observed outcome regression function inherits a jump.\pause

<<rd-motivation-pictures, echo=FALSE, fig=TRUE, height=5.2, width=8>>=
  suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ggplot2))

  c0 <- 6
  x <- seq(0, 10, length.out = 400)

  # Smooth potential outcome regression functions (continuous at c0)
  m0 <- function(x) 0.45 * x + 1.2 * sin(x / 1.6) + 0.2
  # Heterogeneous treatment effects: tau(x) varies with x
  tau_x <- function(x) 1.6 + 0.35 * sin((x - 1.5) / 1.3) + 0.08 * (x - 5)
  m1 <- function(x) m0(x) + tau_x(x)

  # SRD assignment probability and observed regression function under SRD
  p_srd <- ifelse(x < c0, 0, 1)
  m_obs <- ifelse(x < c0, m0(x), m1(x))

  panel1 <- "Fig. 1. Assignment probabilities (SRD)."
  panel2 <- "Fig. 2. Potential and observed outcome regression functions."

  df_assign <- data.frame(panel = panel1, x = x, y = p_srd)

  df_potential <- rbind(
    data.frame(panel = panel2, x = x, y = m0(x), curve = "Y(0)"),
    data.frame(panel = panel2, x = x, y = m1(x), curve = "Y(1)")
  )
  df_potential$source <- "Potential"

  df_obs <- data.frame(panel = panel2, x = x, y = m_obs, source = "Observed")

  df_jump <- data.frame(panel = panel2, x = c0, y0 = m0(c0), y1 = m1(c0))

  p <- ggplot() +
    geom_vline(xintercept = c0, linewidth = 0.5, color = "gray35") +
    geom_step(data = df_assign, aes(x, y), linewidth = 0.7, color = "black") +
    geom_line(
      data = df_potential,
      aes(x, y, group = curve, linetype = source),
      linewidth = 0.6,
      color = "black"
    ) +
    geom_line(
      data = df_obs,
      aes(x, y, linetype = source),
      linewidth = 0.8,
      color = "black"
    ) +
    geom_segment(
      data = df_jump,
      aes(x = x, xend = x, y = y0, yend = y1),
      linewidth = 0.6,
      color = "black"
    ) +
    facet_grid(panel ~ ., scales = "free_y") +
    scale_linetype_manual(values = c(Potential = "22", Observed = "solid")) +
    labs(x = "Forcing variable X", y = NULL) +
    guides(linetype = guide_legend(title = NULL)) +
    theme_classic(base_size = 12) +
    theme(
      strip.background = element_blank(),
      strip.text.y = element_text(angle = 0, hjust = 0),
      legend.position = "bottom",
      panel.spacing = grid::unit(0.7, "lines")
    )

  print(p)
@
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}[fragile]{Motivating FRD: imprecise sorting and imperfect compliance}
\small
Often there is a cutoff-based \textbf{eligibility rule} but \textbf{treatment receipt is imperfect}.\pause

\begin{wideitemize}
\item Define eligibility (the instrument): \(Z_i=\one\{X_i\ge c\}\).\pause
\item With imprecise sorting / imperfect enforcement / imperfect take-up, \(D_i\) does not equal \(Z_i\) for everyone.\pause
\item Then \(\Pr[D_i=1\mid X_i=x]\) still has a \emph{jump} at \(c\), but not from 0 to 1 (fuzzy RD).\pause
\end{wideitemize}

<<rd-fuzzy-imprecise-sorting, echo=FALSE, fig=TRUE, height=3.4, width=8>>=
  suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ggplot2))

  c0 <- 6
  xg <- seq(0, 10, length.out = 400)

  # A simple FRD "first stage": probability shifts at c0 but is not 0/1.
  p_frd <- pmin(pmax(0.12 + 0.03 * (xg - 5) + 0.55 * (xg >= c0), 0.02), 0.98)
  df_p <- data.frame(panel = "Pr(D=1 | X=x)", x = xg, p = p_frd)

  # Simulated receipt showing treated on both sides due to imperfect compliance.
  n <- 900
  xs <- runif(n, 0, 10)
  ps <- pmin(pmax(0.12 + 0.03 * (xs - 5) + 0.55 * (xs >= c0), 0.02), 0.98)
  ds <- rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = ps)
  df_s <- data.frame(panel = "Observed receipt D", x = xs, d = ds)

  ggplot() +
    geom_vline(xintercept = c0, linewidth = 0.5, color = "gray35") +
    geom_step(data = df_p, aes(x, p), linewidth = 0.8, color = "black") +
    geom_point(
      data = df_s,
      aes(x, d),
      alpha = 0.35,
      size = 1.1,
      position = position_jitter(height = 0.06, width = 0)
	    ) +
	    facet_grid(panel ~ ., scales = "free_y") +
	    scale_y_continuous(limits = c(-0.12, 1.12), breaks = c(0, 0.5, 1)) +
	    labs(x = "Forcing variable X", y = NULL) +
	    theme_classic(base_size = 12) +
	    theme(
	      strip.background = element_blank(),
      strip.text.y = element_text(angle = 0, hjust = 0),
      panel.spacing = grid::unit(0.7, "lines")
    )
@
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{RD assumptions (sufficient conditions, in our notation)}
\small
We observe \((Y_i, D_i, X_i)\), where \(X_i\) is the forcing variable and \(D_i\in\{0,1\}\) is treatment/receipt.\pause

\begin{wideitemize}
\item \textbf{SUTVA:} \(Y_i = Y_i(1)\cdot D_i + Y_i(0)\cdot (1-D_i)\).\pause
\item \textbf{Continuity of potential-outcome CEFs at the cutoff:} for \(d\in\{0,1\}\),
\[
\lim_{\ell\downarrow 0}\E[Y_i(d)\mid X_i=c+\ell]
=\lim_{\ell\downarrow 0}\E[Y_i(d)\mid X_i=c-\ell]
=\E[Y_i(d)\mid X_i=c].
\]\pause
\item \textbf{Density/positivity near the cutoff:} \(f_X\) is continuous at \(c\) and \(f_X(c)>0\) (so there are observations arbitrarily close to \(c\) on both sides).\pause
\end{wideitemize}

\vspace{0.25em}
\scriptsize
Strictly speaking, continuity of \(f_X\) is not required for identification, but it is often a useful (and checkable) diagnostic: big density changes can signal sorting/manipulation.
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{SRD identification: the jump equals the ATE at the cutoff}
\small
Define the SRD estimand (Imbens--Lemieux):
\[
\tau_{SRD}\equiv \E\!\left[Y_i(1)-Y_i(0)\mid X_i=c\right].
\]\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
In \textbf{sharp RD}, \(D_i=\one\{X_i\ge c\}\). Using SUTVA and continuity at \(c\):\pause
\begin{align*}
&\lim_{\ell\downarrow 0}\E[Y_i\mid X_i=c+\ell]-\lim_{\ell\downarrow 0}\E[Y_i\mid X_i=c-\ell] \\
&= \lim_{\ell\downarrow 0}\E\!\left[Y_i(1)\mid X_i=c+\ell\right]-\lim_{\ell\downarrow 0}\E\!\left[Y_i(0)\mid X_i=c-\ell\right] \\
&= \E\!\left[Y_i(1)\mid X_i=c\right]-\E\!\left[Y_i(0)\mid X_i=c\right] \\
&= \E\!\left[Y_i(1)-Y_i(0)\mid X_i=c\right] \\
&\equiv \tau_{SRD}.
\end{align*}

\vspace{0.25em}
\pause
\textbf{Interpretation:} the jump in \(\E[Y\mid X=x]\) at \(x=c\) equals the ATE for units at the cutoff.
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}[fragile]{Simulated toy RD: raw data}
\small
Before smoothing or binning, the data are noisy: you cannot read the jump off of individual points.\pause

<<rd-toy-raw, echo=FALSE, fig=TRUE, height=3.2, width=7>>=
  suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ggplot2))

  ggplot(toy, aes(x = X, y = Y, color = factor(D))) +
    geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linewidth = 0.5, color = "gray35") +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.25, size = 1) +
    scale_color_manual(values = c("0" = "gray40", "1" = "gray40")) +
    labs(x = "Forcing variable X", y = "Outcome Y") +
    theme_classic(base_size = 12) +
    theme(legend.position = "none")
@
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Step 1 in practice: a binned scatter plot}
\small
Plot bin means of \(Y\) against \(X\), separately on each side of the cutoff (do not smooth across \(c\)).\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
If the plot shows many jumps of similar size away from \(c\), interpreting the jump at \(c\) as causal is harder.
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}[fragile]{Simulated toy RD: binned means}
\small
By construction, the true cutoff effect is \(\tau_{SRD}=1\) in this toy example.\pause

<<rd-toy-bins, echo=FALSE, fig=TRUE, height=3.2, width=7>>=
bm <- rd_bin_means(toy, c = 0, binwidth = 0.1, x_min = -2, x_max = 2)

df_bins <- rbind(
  data.frame(side = "Left of c", x = bm$x_l, y = bm$y_l),
  data.frame(side = "Right of c", x = bm$x_r, y = bm$y_r)
)

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ggplot2))

ggplot(df_bins, aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linewidth = 0.6, color = "firebrick") +
  geom_point(size = 1.5, alpha = 0.8, color = "gray35") +
  annotate("text", x = 0.05, y = max(df_bins$y), label = "cutoff c", hjust = 0, vjust = 1, color = "firebrick", size = 3.4) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(-2, 2)) +
  labs(
    x = "Forcing variable X",
    y = "Mean outcome in bin",
    title = "Binned means (no smoothing across the cutoff)"
  ) +
  theme_classic(base_size = 12) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 11))
@
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Estimation: local linear regression at a boundary}
\small
Imbens--Lemieux recommendation: local linear regression, fit separately on each side using only \(|X_i-c|\le h\).\pause

\begin{wideitemize}
\item With a uniform kernel, this is ``OLS within bandwidth \(h\)'' on each side.\pause
\item Estimate \(\hat\tau(h)\) as the difference between the fitted intercepts at \(c\).\pause
\end{wideitemize}

\vspace{0.25em}
\textbf{Key practice point:} report robustness to multiple bandwidths.
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}[fragile]{Toy RD: local linear fit for one bandwidth}
\small
Example with bandwidth \(h=0.5\): fit a line to \(Y\) vs.\ \((X-c)\) on each side using only \(|X-c|\le h\).\pause

<<rd-toy-ll-one, echo=FALSE, fig=TRUE, height=3.2, width=7>>=
h <- 0.5
ll <- rd_ll_uniform(toy, c = 0, h = h, y = "Y", x = "X")
bm <- rd_bin_means(toy, c = 0, binwidth = 0.1, x_min = -2, x_max = 2)

df_bins <- rbind(
  data.frame(side = "Left of c", x = bm$x_l, y = bm$y_l),
  data.frame(side = "Right of c", x = bm$x_r, y = bm$y_r)
)

grid_l <- seq(-h, 0, length.out = 50)
grid_r <- seq(0, h, length.out = 50)

df_fit <- rbind(
  data.frame(side = "Left fit", x = grid_l, y = ll$a_l + coef(ll$fit_l)[2] * grid_l),
  data.frame(side = "Right fit", x = grid_r, y = ll$a_r + coef(ll$fit_r)[2] * grid_r)
)

note <- sprintf("tau_hat(h)=%.3f\nN_left=%d, N_right=%d", ll$tau_hat, ll$n_l, ll$n_r)
y_note <- max(c(df_bins$y, df_fit$y))

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ggplot2))

ggplot() +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linewidth = 0.6, color = "firebrick") +
  geom_point(data = df_bins, aes(x = x, y = y), size = 1.4, alpha = 0.75, color = "gray45") +
  geom_line(data = df_fit, aes(x = x, y = y), linewidth = 1.1, color = "navy") +
  annotate("text", x = -1.95, y = y_note, label = note, hjust = 0, vjust = 1, size = 3.3) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(-2, 2)) +
  labs(
    x = "X",
    y = "Mean Y in bin",
    title = sprintf("Local linear (uniform kernel), bandwidth h = %.2f", h)
  ) +
  theme_classic(base_size = 12) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 11))
@
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}[fragile]{Toy RD: bandwidth sensitivity}
\small
Compute \(\hat\tau(h)\) for a range of bandwidths \(h\).\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
Data-driven ``optimal'' bandwidth selectors are useful, but you should still report sensitivity; see Imbens and Kalyanaraman (2012).\pause

<<rd-toy-bandwidth, echo=FALSE, fig=TRUE, height=3.2, width=7>>=
hs <- c(0.15, 0.25, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8, 1.0)
ests <- sapply(hs, function(h) rd_ll_uniform(toy, c = 0, h = h)$tau_hat)

df_bw <- data.frame(h = hs, tau_hat = as.numeric(ests))

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ggplot2))

ggplot(df_bw, aes(x = h, y = tau_hat)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = true_tau_at_c, linewidth = 0.7, linetype = "22", color = "firebrick") +
  geom_line(linewidth = 0.9, color = "gray20") +
  geom_point(size = 2.0, color = "gray20") +
  annotate("text", x = max(df_bw$h), y = true_tau_at_c, label = "true tau=1", vjust = -0.8, hjust = 1, color = "firebrick", size = 3.4) +
  labs(
    x = "Bandwidth h",
    y = "Estimated jump tau_hat(h)",
    title = "Sensitivity of the RD estimate to bandwidth choice"
  ) +
  theme_classic(base_size = 12) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 11))
@
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Diagnostics: what to check (Imbens--Lemieux)}
\small
\begin{wideitemize}
\item \textbf{Manipulation/sorting:} does the density of \(X\) jump at \(c\)? (McCrary test)\pause
\item \textbf{Covariate continuity:} do predetermined covariates jump at \(c\)?\pause
\item \textbf{Placebo cutoffs:} do you see similar jumps at other values?\pause
\end{wideitemize}

\vspace{0.25em}
\textbf{Interpretation:} these checks probe whether ``just below vs.\ just above \(c\)'' is a credible comparison.
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}[fragile]{Toy RD diagnostics: density and covariate balance}
\small
In the toy DGP there is no manipulation by construction, and the extra covariate \(Z\) is smooth in \(X\).\pause

<<rd-toy-diag, echo=FALSE, fig=TRUE, height=3.2, width=7>>=
bmz <- rd_bin_means(transform(toy, Y = Z), c = 0, binwidth = 0.1, x_min = -2, x_max = 2)

df_z <- rbind(
  data.frame(panel = "Predetermined covariate Z", x = bmz$x_l, y = bmz$y_l),
  data.frame(panel = "Predetermined covariate Z", x = bmz$x_r, y = bmz$y_r)
)

toy_hist <- transform(toy, panel = "Density of X (toy)")

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ggplot2))

ggplot() +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linewidth = 0.6, color = "firebrick") +
  geom_histogram(
    data = toy_hist,
    aes(x = X),
    bins = 40,
    fill = "gray80",
    color = "white"
  ) +
  geom_point(
    data = df_z,
    aes(x = x, y = y),
    size = 1.3,
    alpha = 0.8,
    color = "gray40"
  ) +
  facet_grid(panel ~ ., scales = "free_y") +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(-2, 2)) +
  labs(x = "X", y = NULL) +
  theme_classic(base_size = 12) +
  theme(
    strip.background = element_blank(),
    strip.text.y = element_text(angle = 0, hjust = 0),
    panel.spacing = grid::unit(0.7, "lines")
  )
@
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{RD in practice: general recommendations (Imbens--Lemieux style)}
\small
\textbf{Local linear within a bandwidth:} estimate the jump at the cutoff by OLS on units with \(|X_i-c|<h\):\pause
\[
Y_i
=
\alpha_0+\tau\cdot D_i+\beta_1(X_i-c)+\beta_2 D_i(X_i-c)+\varepsilon_i.
\]
\pause
With a uniform (rectangular) kernel, this is local linear regression at a boundary; \(\hat\tau\) estimates the cutoff jump.\pause

\begin{wideitemize}
\item \textbf{Bandwidth choice:} use a data-driven ``optimal'' bandwidth (Imbens and Kalyanaraman, 2012), but still report sensitivity across multiple \(h\)'s.\pause
\item \textbf{Inference:} use robust standard errors (or the bootstrap); show the estimated CEF within the bandwidth.\pause
\item \textbf{Robustness:} report estimates varying polynomial order/specification and bandwidth.\pause
\item \textbf{Diagnostics:} test continuity of predetermined covariates and of the density/PDF of \(X\) at \(c\) (McCrary-type check).\pause
\end{wideitemize}
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{RD robustness: specification tests (what to report)}
\small
Assess robustness by checking whether the ``local comparison'' story is supported in the data:\pause

\begin{wideitemize}
\item \textbf{Covariate continuity:} look for jumps in predetermined covariates at \(c\).\pause
\item \textbf{Density continuity:} test for discontinuities in the conditional density of \(X\) at \(c\) (sorting/manipulation).\pause
\item \textbf{Placebo cutoffs:} check whether \(\E[Y\mid X=x]\) shows discontinuities at other values of \(x\).\pause
\item \textbf{Bandwidth + specification sensitivity:} vary \(h\) and the functional form, and report estimates \emph{with and without} additional covariates (as precision adjustment).\pause
\end{wideitemize}
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Case 2: fuzzy RD (FRD) designs --- practical workflow}
\small
FRD adds one key complication: treatment receipt \(D_i\) is not perfectly determined by eligibility \(Z_i=\one\{X_i\ge c\}\).\pause

\begin{wideitemize}
\item \textbf{Graphs:} make the binned outcome plot \emph{and} graph \(\Pr(D_i=1\mid X_i=x)\) (first stage) near \(c\).\pause
\item \textbf{Estimation:} estimate \(\tau_{FRD}\) using TSLS (numerically equivalent to the local Wald ratio \(\Delta_Y/\Delta_D\)).\pause
\item \textbf{Inference:} use robust TSLS standard errors (or bootstrap); a plug-in approach is another option.\pause
\item \textbf{Bandwidth:} choose an ``optimal'' bandwidth as a starting point (IK 2012 / modified CV ideas), and still report sensitivity.\pause
\item \textbf{Robustness:} apply the SRD specification tests; also compare the FRD estimate to standard unconfoundedness-based estimates as a sanity check.\pause
\end{wideitemize}
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}[fragile]{Toy FRD: binned outcomes and treatment probability}
\small
In FRD, it is helpful to plot the reduced-form jump in \(Y\) \emph{and} the first-stage jump in \(D\).\pause

<<frd-toy-bins, echo=FALSE, fig=TRUE, height=4.0, width=8>>=
  suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ggplot2))

  bm_y <- rd_bin_means(toy_frd, c = 0, binwidth = 0.1, x_min = -2, x_max = 2)
  bm_d <- rd_bin_means(transform(toy_frd, Y = D), c = 0, binwidth = 0.1, x_min = -2, x_max = 2)

  df_y <- rbind(
    data.frame(panel = "Binned mean of outcome Y", x = bm_y$x_l, y = bm_y$y_l),
    data.frame(panel = "Binned mean of outcome Y", x = bm_y$x_r, y = bm_y$y_r)
  )

  df_d <- rbind(
    data.frame(panel = "Binned Pr(D=1 | X in bin)", x = bm_d$x_l, y = bm_d$y_l),
    data.frame(panel = "Binned Pr(D=1 | X in bin)", x = bm_d$x_r, y = bm_d$y_r)
  )

  df_plot <- rbind(df_y, df_d)

  ggplot(df_plot, aes(x = x, y = y)) +
    geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linewidth = 0.5, color = "gray35") +
    geom_point(size = 1.2, alpha = 0.7, color = "gray30") +
    facet_grid(panel ~ ., scales = "free_y") +
    labs(x = "Forcing variable X (cutoff at 0)", y = NULL) +
    theme_classic(base_size = 12) +
    theme(
      strip.background = element_blank(),
      strip.text.y = element_text(angle = 0, hjust = 0),
      panel.spacing = grid::unit(0.7, "lines")
    )
@
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Fuzzy RD: the local Wald estimand}
\scriptsize
Define outcome and treatment jumps at the cutoff:\pause
\[
\Delta_Y=\lim_{x\downarrow c}\E[Y\mid X=x]-\lim_{x\uparrow c}\E[Y\mid X=x],
\]
\[
\Delta_D=\lim_{x\downarrow c}\E[D\mid X=x]-\lim_{x\uparrow c}\E[D\mid X=x].
\]
\pause
Then the fuzzy RD estimand is the local Wald ratio:
\[
\tau_{FRD}=\frac{\Delta_Y}{\Delta_D}.
\]

\vspace{0.25em}
\pause
Equivalently, written directly in terms of the limits:
\[
\tau_{FRD}
=
\frac{
\lim_{x\downarrow c}\E[Y\mid X=x]-\lim_{x\uparrow c}\E[Y\mid X=x]
}{
\lim_{x\downarrow c}\E[D\mid X=x]-\lim_{x\uparrow c}\E[D\mid X=x]
}.
\]


\vspace{0.25em}
\pause
\textbf{Note:} in FRD, treatment receipt can be endogenous, so it is \emph{not} generally true that
\[
\E\!\left[Y_i(d)\mid D_i=d,\ X_i=x\right]=\E\!\left[Y_i(d)\mid X_i=x\right].
\]
\pause
This equality would follow under an unconfoundedness-type assumption, but FRD identification of causal effects does not require it.\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
\pause
Under additional assumptions (monotonicity + exclusion-type conditions), \(\tau_{FRD}\) is a LATE for compliers at the cutoff:
\[
\tau_{FRD}
=
\E\!\left[Y_i(1)-Y_i(0)\mid \text{unit \(i\) is a complier},\ X_i=c\right].
\]
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{FRD monotonicity and compliance types (RD analog of IV)}
\small
To interpret FRD as a LATE, it is useful to define potential treatment status under \emph{counterfactual cutoff values}.\pause

\begin{wideitemize}
\item Let \(D_i(c')\in\{0,1\}\) denote whether unit \(i\) would be treated if the cutoff were set to \(c'\) (keeping the unit's forcing value \(X_i\) fixed).\pause
\item \textbf{Monotonicity at the cutoff (Imbens--Lemieux):} \(D_i(c')\) is non-increasing in \(c'\) at \(c'=c\).\pause
\end{wideitemize}

\vspace{0.25em}
\pause
Define \textbf{compliance status} by how \(D_i(c')\) changes as the cutoff crosses the unit's \(X_i\):\pause
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Complier:} \(\lim_{c'\downarrow X_i} D_i(c')=0\) and \(\lim_{c'\uparrow X_i} D_i(c')=1\).\pause
\item \textbf{Never-taker:} \(\lim_{c'\downarrow X_i} D_i(c')=0\) and \(\lim_{c'\uparrow X_i} D_i(c')=0\).\pause
\item \textbf{Always-taker:} \(\lim_{c'\downarrow X_i} D_i(c')=1\) and \(\lim_{c'\uparrow X_i} D_i(c')=1\).\pause
\item \textbf{Defier:} \(\lim_{c'\downarrow X_i} D_i(c')=1\) and \(\lim_{c'\uparrow X_i} D_i(c')=0\).\pause
\end{itemize}

\vspace{0.25em}
\pause
\scriptsize
Interpretation (with the usual assignment direction \(D=\one\{X\ge c\}\)): if the cutoff is set just \emph{below} \(X_i\), unit \(i\) is treated; if the cutoff is set just \emph{above} \(X_i\), unit \(i\) is not treated. Under monotonicity, there are no ``defiers'' (units whose treatment would increase when the cutoff is raised).
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{transitionframe}
\centering
\color{white}
\Large Next: differences in differences (DiD) and panel data
\end{transitionframe}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{DiD setup: two groups, two periods}
\small
DiD uses changes over time plus a comparison group.\pause

\begin{wideitemize}
\item Groups: \(G_i\in\{0,1\}\) (1 = treated group, 0 = comparison group)\pause
\item Time: \(t\in\{0,1\}\) (0 = pre, 1 = post)\pause
\item Treatment: \(D_{it}=\one\{G_i=1\}\cdot \one\{t=1\}\) (2x2 case)\pause
\item Potential outcomes: \(Y_{it}(1),Y_{it}(0)\), observed \(Y_{it}=Y_{it}(D_{it})\)\pause
\end{wideitemize}
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}[fragile]{DiD picture: noisy raw data vs.\ group means}
\small
Raw panel data are noisy; DiD is about \emph{average} changes (thick lines show the expected group means in a toy DGP with parallel pre-trends).\pause

<<did-toy-plot, echo=FALSE, fig=TRUE, height=3.4, width=7.5>>=
  suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ggplot2))

  # Use the toy DGP's expected means (so the pre-trends are exactly parallel in the figure).
  t0 <- min(did_toy$t[did_toy$D == 1])
  t_vals <- sort(unique(did_toy$t))
  gmeans <- expand.grid(t = t_vals, group = c("control", "treated"))
  gmeans$treated <- as.numeric(gmeans$group == "treated")
  gmeans$post <- as.numeric(gmeans$t >= t0)
  gmeans$D <- gmeans$treated * gmeans$post

  level_gap <- 0.8 * gmeans$treated
  common_trend <- 0.30 * gmeans$t
  te <- 1.2 + 0.2 * pmax(0, gmeans$t - t0)

  gmeans$Y <- 2.0 + level_gap + common_trend + gmeans$D * te

  # Plot time relative to the pre/post boundary: 0 = last pre period, 1 = first post period.
  t_rel0 <- t0 - 1
  did_toy_plot <- did_toy
  did_toy_plot$t_rel <- did_toy_plot$t - t_rel0
  gmeans$t_rel <- gmeans$t - t_rel0

  ggplot(did_toy_plot, aes(x = t_rel, y = Y)) +
    geom_vline(xintercept = 1, linewidth = 0.5, color = "gray35") +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.03, size = 0.7, color = "gray40") +
    geom_line(
      data = gmeans,
      aes(x = t_rel, y = Y, color = group, group = group),
      linewidth = 1.2
    ) +
    scale_color_manual(values = c(control = "gray20", treated = "firebrick")) +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = sort(unique(did_toy_plot$t_rel))) +
    labs(x = "Time (0 = pre, 1 = post)", y = "Outcome Y") +
    theme_classic(base_size = 12) +
    theme(legend.position = "bottom", legend.title = element_blank())
@
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{2x2 DiD estimand}
\small
The DiD estimand is the difference in average changes:
\[
\begin{aligned}
\tau_{DiD}
\equiv\;&
\Big(\E[Y\mid G=1,t=1]-\E[Y\mid G=1,t=0]\Big)\\
&-\Big(\E[Y\mid G=0,t=1]-\E[Y\mid G=0,t=0]\Big).
\end{aligned}
\]\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
Interpretation: remove (i) time shocks common to both groups and (ii) time-invariant level differences between groups.
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{2x2 DiD as a regression}
\small
In the 2x2 case, the DiD estimator equals the coefficient on the interaction term in:
\[
Y_{it}=\alpha+\gamma\,G_i+\lambda\,\text{Post}_t+\tau\,(G_i\cdot \text{Post}_t)+\varepsilon_{it},
\]
where \(\text{Post}_t\equiv \one\{t=1\}\).\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
\begin{wideitemize}
\item \(\gamma\): baseline level difference (treated vs comparison)\pause
\item \(\lambda\): common time shock (post vs pre)\pause
\item \(\tau\): DiD estimate of the treatment effect under parallel trends\pause
\end{wideitemize}

\vspace{0.25em}
\scriptsize
Adding covariates is typically for precision (and for making parallel trends more plausible), but it does not replace the design assumption.
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Parallel trends + overlap}
\small
The key design assumption is about \emph{counterfactual} trends under no treatment:\pause
\[
\E[Y_{i1}(0)-Y_{i0}(0)\mid G_i=1]
=
\E[Y_{i1}(0)-Y_{i0}(0)\mid G_i=0].
\]\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
\textbf{Positivity/overlap (2x2):} \(\Pr(G_i=1)\in(0,1)\), and we observe both groups in both periods so each cell mean \(\E[Y\mid G=g,t=t]\) is well-defined.\pause
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Identification under parallel trends}
\small
Under parallel trends (and SUTVA), \(\tau_{DiD}\) identifies the average treatment effect for the treated group in the post period:\pause
\[
\tau_{DiD}=\E[Y_{i1}(1)-Y_{i1}(0)\mid G_i=1].
\]

\vspace{0.25em}
\pause
\scriptsize
\textbf{One formal (strong) ``common trends'' condition:} letting \(\Delta Y_i(d)\equiv Y_{i1}(d)-Y_{i0}(d)\), assume
\[
\big(\Delta Y_i(0),\Delta Y_i(1)\big)\ \perp\ (D_{i0},D_{i1}).
\]
This implies the mean parallel-trends condition, but it is stronger than what is needed for identification.\pause
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{What can go wrong? (threats to parallel trends)}
\small
Parallel trends is a claim about the \emph{untreated counterfactual} for the treated group.\pause

\begin{wideitemize}
\item \textbf{Differential shocks:} treated group faces a shock in the post period unrelated to treatment.\pause
\item \textbf{Composition changes:} who is observed in each group changes over time.\pause
\item \textbf{Anticipation:} treatment affects behavior before the official start.\pause
\item \textbf{Spillovers:} the comparison group is affected indirectly.\pause
\end{wideitemize}

\vspace{0.25em}
\textbf{Pre-trends:} event-study leads are useful diagnostics; interpret null pre-trends with caution (power can be limited).
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Inference: serial correlation (Bertrand--Duflo--Mullainathan 2004)}
\small
In DiD with repeated observations over time, errors are often serially correlated.\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
\textbf{Recall the 2x2 regression:}
\[
Y_{it}=\alpha+\gamma\,G_i+\lambda\,\text{Post}_t+\tau\,(G_i\cdot \text{Post}_t)+\varepsilon_{it}.
\]\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
\textbf{What ``serial correlation'' means:} for the same unit \(i\),
\[
\text{Cov}(\varepsilon_{it},\varepsilon_{is})\neq 0\quad\text{for }t\neq s.
\]\pause

\begin{wideitemize}
\item If you treat \(\{\varepsilon_{it}\}\) as i.i.d.\ across \((i,t)\), standard errors can be much too small.\pause
\item Practical default: cluster standard errors at the unit level (or at the level of treatment assignment/policy variation).\pause
\item With few clusters: be cautious (cluster-robust SEs can be unreliable).
\end{wideitemize}

\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{What to cluster on? (rule of thumb)}
\small
\begin{wideitemize}
\item Cluster at the level of \textbf{treatment assignment / policy variation}.\pause
\item If treatment varies at the unit level over time, unit-level clustering is a common default.\pause
\item If treatment varies at a higher level (e.g., state policy), cluster at that higher level (often two-way with time if needed).\pause
\item With \textbf{few clusters}: consider alternatives (aggregation, randomization-style inference, or methods designed for small \(G\)).\pause
\end{wideitemize}
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{transitionframe}
\centering
\color{white}
\Large From 2x2 DiD to fixed effects regressions
\end{transitionframe}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{One-way fixed effects (unit FE): what is the regression?}
\small
\textbf{One-way FE} means we include fixed effects for the unit (subject) \(i\), but not time fixed effects.\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
\textbf{Regression form:}
\[
Y_{it}=\alpha_i+\tau\,D_{it}+u_{it}.
\]
\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
\textbf{Equivalent ``within'' form (demean within unit):}
\[
Y_{it}-\bar Y_i=\tau\,(D_{it}-\bar D_i)+(u_{it}-\bar u_i),
\]
where \(\bar Y_i\equiv \frac{1}{T}\sum_{t}Y_{it}\) and similarly for \(\bar D_i\).\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
\textbf{Two-period special case:} with \(t\in\{0,1\}\), this is numerically equivalent to first differences:
\[
\Delta Y_i=\tau\,\Delta D_i+\Delta u_i.
\]
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{One-way FE as generalized first differences (when is it causal?)}
\small
In one-way FE, identification comes from \emph{within-unit timing} of treatment.\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
The maintained conditional-mean model is:
\[
\E[Y_{it}\mid D_{it}, i]=\alpha_i+\tau\,D_{it}.
\]\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
\begin{wideitemize}
\item \textbf{Analogy:} with two periods, one-way FE equals the first-difference estimator.\pause
\item \textbf{Multi-period intuition:} it generalizes first differences by comparing each unit to itself over many periods.\pause
\item \textbf{Consistency requires} that (conditional on the unit effect \(\alpha_i\)) changes in \(D_{it}\) are as-if random with respect to time-varying shocks in \(u_{it}\) (a ``no time-varying confounding'' / strict exogeneity-type condition).\pause
\item If there are \emph{common period shocks} correlated with \(D_{it}\), add period fixed effects \(\lambda_t\) (TWFE) to absorb them.\pause
\end{wideitemize}
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Example: when one-way FE can be credible}
\small
One-way FE can be credible when treatment timing is as-if random within unit.\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
\textbf{Example (crossover randomization):}\pause
\begin{wideitemize}
\item Units \(i\): students; periods \(t\): weeks.\pause
\item Each week, each student is randomly assigned \(D_{it}\in\{0,1\}\) (e.g., feature on/off).\pause
\item Then \(D_{it}\perp u_{it}\mid i\), so \(\E[u_{it}\mid D_{it},i]=0\) and one-way FE identifies \(\tau\) in \(Y_{it}=\alpha_i+\tau D_{it}+u_{it}\).\pause
\item We need to assume no within-person spillovers/sufficient washout time between measures. 
\item If treatment probabilities drift over time or treatment is rolled out later for everyone, common time shocks can correlate with \(D_{it}\); then add period FE \(\lambda_t\) (TWFE).\pause
\end{wideitemize}
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{From 2x2 to many periods: TWFE}
\small
With panel data, a common starting point is the two-way fixed effects (TWFE) regression:\pause
\[
Y_{it}=\alpha_i+\lambda_t+\tau\,D_{it}+\varepsilon_{it}.
\]\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
\begin{wideitemize}
\item If there is one treated group and one treatment time, TWFE aligns with 2x2 DiD.\pause
\item With staggered adoption and heterogeneous effects, TWFE can mix many comparisons in hard-to-interpret ways.\pause
\end{wideitemize}
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{TWFE with two periods: first differences and generalized DiD}
\small
With only two periods \(t\in\{1,2\}\), TWFE
\[
Y_{it}=\alpha_i+\lambda_t+\tau\,D_{it}+\varepsilon_{it}
\]
is algebraically equivalent to a first-differences regression.\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
Difference within unit \(i\):
\[
\Delta Y_i\equiv Y_{i2}-Y_{i1}
=
(\lambda_2-\lambda_1)
\;+\;
\tau\,\Delta D_i
\;+\;
\Delta \varepsilon_i,
\]
where \(\Delta D_i\equiv D_{i2}-D_{i1}\) and \(\Delta \varepsilon_i\equiv \varepsilon_{i2}-\varepsilon_{i1}\).\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
So estimating TWFE with two periods gives the same \(\hat\tau\) as OLS of \(\Delta Y_i\) on \(\Delta D_i\) \textbf{with a constant} (the constant estimates \(\lambda_2-\lambda_1\)).\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
In the 2x2 DiD setup with no pre-treatment (\(D_{i1}=0\) for all \(i\)) and \(D_{i2}=\one\{G_i=1\}\), we have \(\Delta D_i=\one\{G_i=1\}\), so
\[
\tau=\E[\Delta Y_i\mid G_i=1]-\E[\Delta Y_i\mid G_i=0],
\]
which is exactly the (generalized) DiD estimator.
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{TWFE in practice (T>2): what you are doing}
\small
\textbf{Dummy-variable form:} TWFE is just OLS with unit and period indicators:
\[
\E[Y_{it}\mid D_{it}, i, t]
=
\tau\,D_{it}
\;+\;
\sum_{j=1}^{n}\alpha_j\,\one\{i=j\}
\;+\;
\sum_{s=1}^{T}\lambda_s\,\one\{t=s\}.
\]\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
\textbf{Interpretation:} \(\hat\tau\) uses within-unit changes in \(D_{it}\), netting out (i) time-invariant unit differences \((\alpha_i)\) and (ii) common shocks in each period \((\lambda_t)\).\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
\textbf{When to trust it:}\pause
\begin{wideitemize}
\item If (in the absence of treatment) treated and comparison observations would follow the same \emph{average} time path after accounting for \(\alpha_i\) and \(\lambda_t\) (a multi-period parallel-trends condition).\pause
\item And there is not ``bad'' time-varying confounding that both moves \(D_{it}\) and directly affects \(Y_{it}\).\pause
\end{wideitemize}
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Example: when TWFE can be credible}
\small
TWFE can be credible when (i) there are common time shocks and (ii) treatment timing is as-if random within unit.\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
\textbf{Example (phased-in random rollout):}\pause
\begin{wideitemize}
\item Units \(i\): schools; periods \(t\): years. Outcome \(Y_{it}\): test scores.\pause
\item A new program is rolled out to schools in a randomized order; \(D_{it}=1\) once school \(i\) receives it.\pause
\item \(\alpha_i\) absorbs time-invariant school differences; \(\lambda_t\) absorbs statewide shocks each year.\pause
\item Random rollout implies \(D_{it}\perp \varepsilon_{it}\mid i,t\), so TWFE can identify an average effect \(\tau\) in \(Y_{it}=\alpha_i+\lambda_t+\tau D_{it}+\varepsilon_{it}\).\pause
\item If effects vary by cohort or by time-since-treatment, the single TWFE coefficient can be hard to interpret (staggered adoption issue).\pause
\end{wideitemize}
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Relating to practice: FE are adjustment, not identification}
\small
Two-way fixed effects adjust for systematic differences across units (\(\alpha_i\)) and systematic shocks across time periods (\(\lambda_t\)). This is often a good idea.\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
\begin{wideitemize}
\item \textbf{But:} FE do not replace a design argument. They do not automatically solve time-varying confounding or differential trends.\pause
\item \textbf{Why pooled OLS / random effects can be a bad idea:} these approaches effectively assume unit heterogeneity is uncorrelated with treatment (e.g., \(\text{Cov}(\alpha_i,D_{it})=0\)); in practice this is often implausible.\pause
\item \textbf{Covariates:} you can add \(X_{it}\) directly; interpret the identifying condition as ``parallel trends conditional on \(X_{it}\).''\pause
\item \textbf{Inference:} use cluster-robust SEs (cluster by unit, or by assignment level) or bootstrap by resampling units.\pause
\end{wideitemize}

\vspace{0.25em}
\scriptsize
See Green, Kim, and Yoon (2001) on pitfalls of ``dirty pooling'' in time-series cross-section settings.
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Assumptions: what identifies causal effects?}
\scriptsize
Fixed effects are adjustment. Identification comes from assumptions about treatment timing and potential outcomes.\pause

\textbf{Staggered adoption notation:} \(G_i\) is unit \(i\)'s first treated period (\(G_i=\infty\) if never treated). \(Y_{it}(g)\) is the potential outcome at time \(t\) if first treated at time \(g\) and treated thereafter.\pause

\begin{wideitemize}
\item \textbf{Randomized timing (strong):} \(G_i\) (or \(\{D_{it}\}\)) is as-if random with respect to \(\{Y_{it}(g)\}\). Stronger than parallel trends.\pause
\item \textbf{No anticipation:} for any \(g\), \(Y_{it}(g)=Y_{it}(\infty)\) for all \(t<g\).\pause
\item \textbf{Invariance to history (strong):} \(Y_{it}(g)=Y_{it}(1)\) for all \(t\ge g\).\pause
\item \textbf{Constant effects across units:} treatment effects do not vary with \(i\).\pause
\item \textbf{Constant effects over time:} treatment effects do not vary with \(t\) or event time \(k=t-g\).\pause
\item \textbf{Bottom line:} different assumptions identify different causal quantities.
\end{wideitemize}
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Event-study regression (multi-period)}
\small
With staggered adoption, a common goal is a dynamic effect profile by event time \(k=t-G_i\).\pause

One regression-style approach is:
\[
Y_{it}=\alpha_i+\lambda_t+\sum_{k\neq -1}\beta_k\,\one\{t-G_i=k\}+\varepsilon_{it},
\]
where \(k=-1\) (one pre period) is omitted as the baseline.\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
\textbf{Interpretation:} \(\beta_k\) are ``effects at event time \(k\)'' \emph{if} the regression targets a clean estimand (this can fail under TWFE with heterogeneous effects).
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Event studies: what we want to see}
\small
An event-study plot shows average effects by event time \(k=t-G_i\) (time relative to first treatment).\pause

\begin{wideitemize}
\item Pre-period coefficients (leads) are a diagnostic for trend violations/anticipation.\pause
\item Post-period coefficients (lags) summarize dynamic treatment effects.\pause
\end{wideitemize}

\vspace{0.25em}
\textbf{Caution:} a good-looking pre-trend plot is helpful, but it is not a proof of parallel trends.
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}[fragile]{Staggered adoption: who is treated when?}
\small
With staggered adoption, different cohorts start treatment in different periods.\pause

<<did-stag-timing, echo=FALSE, fig=TRUE, height=3.9, width=7.8>>=
  suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ggplot2))

  unit_df <- unique(did_stag[c("id", "group")])
  unit_df <- unit_df[order(unit_df$group, unit_df$id), ]

  n_show <- 20
  ids_show <- unlist(tapply(unit_df$id, unit_df$group, function(v) head(v, n_show)))

  df_vis <- subset(did_stag, id %in% ids_show)
  df_vis$group <- factor(df_vis$group, levels = c("never", "early", "late"))
  df_vis$id_plot <- ave(df_vis$id, df_vis$group, FUN = function(x) as.integer(factor(x, levels = sort(unique(x)))))

  g_vals <- sort(unique(df_vis$G[is.finite(df_vis$G)]))

  ggplot(df_vis, aes(x = t, y = factor(id_plot), fill = factor(D))) +
    geom_tile(color = "white", linewidth = 0.15) +
    geom_vline(xintercept = g_vals, linewidth = 0.4, linetype = "22", color = "gray35") +
    facet_grid(group ~ ., scales = "free_y", space = "free_y") +
    scale_fill_manual(
      values = c("0" = "gray90", "1" = "firebrick"),
      breaks = c("0", "1"),
      labels = c("Untreated", "Treated"),
      name = "D_it"
    ) +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = sort(unique(df_vis$t))) +
    labs(x = "Time t", y = "Units (sample)") +
    theme_classic(base_size = 12) +
    theme(
      strip.background = element_blank(),
      strip.text.y = element_text(angle = 0, hjust = 0),
      axis.text.y = element_blank(),
      axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
      legend.position = "bottom",
      panel.spacing = grid::unit(0.6, "lines")
    )
@
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}[fragile]{Parallel trends with staggered adoption (conceptual)}
\small
Three cohorts: never treated (U), early treated at \(k\), late treated at \(l\).\pause

<<did-stag-parallel-trends, echo=FALSE, fig=TRUE, height=3.4, width=7.8>>=
  suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ggplot2))

  t <- 1:20
  k <- 7
  l <- 14

  b <- 0.60  # common trend slope (parallel trends in untreated outcomes)
  y_u <- 5 + b * t
  y_early0 <- 18 + b * t
  y_late0 <- 10 + b * t

  te_early <- 10
  te_late <- 15
  y_early <- y_early0 + ifelse(t >= k, te_early, 0)
  y_late <- y_late0 + ifelse(t >= l, te_late, 0)

  df <- rbind(
    data.frame(group = "U", t = t, y = y_u),
    data.frame(group = "k", t = t, y = y_early),
    data.frame(group = "l", t = t, y = y_late)
  )

  # Line segments that do not connect across the jumps at k and l.
  df_line <- rbind(
    data.frame(group = "U", t = t, y = y_u, seg = "U"),
    data.frame(group = "k", t = t[t < k], y = y_early[t < k], seg = "k_pre"),
    data.frame(group = "k", t = t[t >= k], y = y_early[t >= k], seg = "k_post"),
    data.frame(group = "l", t = t[t < l], y = y_late[t < l], seg = "l_pre"),
    data.frame(group = "l", t = t[t >= l], y = y_late[t >= l], seg = "l_post")
  )

  jumps <- data.frame(
    x = c(k, l),
    y0 = c(y_early0[t == k], y_late0[t == l]),
    y1 = c(y_early[t == k], y_late[t == l])
  )

  y_ann <- min(df$y) - 3

  ggplot() +
    geom_vline(xintercept = c(k, l), linewidth = 0.6, color = "firebrick") +
    geom_line(
      data = df_line[df_line$group == "U", ],
      aes(x = t, y = y),
      linewidth = 1.4, color = "gray55"
    ) +
    geom_line(
      data = df_line[df_line$group != "U", ],
      aes(x = t, y = y, group = seg),
      linewidth = 0.9, color = "black"
    ) +
    geom_segment(
      data = jumps,
      aes(x = x, xend = x, y = y0, yend = y1),
      linetype = 2, linewidth = 0.8, color = "black"
    ) +
    geom_point(
      data = df[df$group == "k", ],
      aes(x = t, y = y),
      shape = 17, size = 2.2, color = "black"
    ) +
    geom_point(
      data = df[df$group == "l", ],
      aes(x = t, y = y),
      shape = 1, size = 2.3, stroke = 0.9, color = "black"
    ) +
    annotate(
      "segment",
      x = min(t), xend = k, y = y_ann, yend = y_ann,
      arrow = grid::arrow(ends = "both", length = grid::unit(0.12, "in")),
      linewidth = 0.5
    ) +
    annotate(
      "segment",
      x = k, xend = l, y = y_ann, yend = y_ann,
      arrow = grid::arrow(ends = "both", length = grid::unit(0.12, "in")),
      linewidth = 0.5
    ) +
    annotate(
      "segment",
      x = l, xend = max(t), y = y_ann, yend = y_ann,
      arrow = grid::arrow(ends = "both", length = grid::unit(0.12, "in")),
      linewidth = 0.5
    ) +
    annotate("text", x = (min(t) + k) / 2, y = y_ann + 0.9, label = "PRE(k)", size = 3.6) +
    annotate("text", x = (k + l) / 2, y = y_ann + 0.9, label = "MID(k,l)", size = 3.6) +
    annotate("text", x = (l + max(t)) / 2, y = y_ann + 0.9, label = "POST(l)", size = 3.6) +
    annotate("text", x = max(t) - 1, y = y_early[max(t)] + 1.2, label = "early cohort", hjust = 1, size = 3.6) +
    annotate("text", x = max(t) - 1, y = y_late[max(t)] - 0.5, label = "late cohort", hjust = 1, size = 3.6) +
    annotate(
      "text",
      x = max(t) - 1, y = y_u[max(t)] - 0.5,
      label = "never treated", hjust = 1, size = 3.6, color = "gray35"
    ) +
    scale_x_continuous(
      breaks = c(min(t), k, l, max(t)),
      labels = c("1", "k", "l", "T")
    ) +
    scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, max(df$y) + 3)) +
    labs(x = "Time", y = "Units of Y") +
    theme_classic(base_size = 12)
@
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Staggered adoption: what can go wrong with TWFE?}
\small
With multiple cohorts and adoption times, TWFE implicitly averages many 2x2 comparisons.\pause

\begin{wideitemize}
\item Some comparisons use already-treated units as controls for later-treated units.\pause
\item Weights can be non-intuitive (and can be negative), so coefficients may not equal the average of cohort-specific effects.\pause
\end{wideitemize}

\vspace{0.25em}
\scriptsize
See Goodman-Bacon (2021) for the decomposition intuition; see Sun \& Abraham (2021) for event-study issues and fixes.
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}[fragile]{Toy staggered adoption: the 2x2 comparisons TWFE mixes}
\small
In this toy example there are two treated cohorts (early, late) and a never-treated cohort.\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
TWFE effectively combines multiple 2x2 DiD comparisons --- including comparisons that use already-treated units as controls.\pause

<<did-stag-2x2-comparisons, echo=FALSE, fig=TRUE, height=3.4, width=7.8>>=
  suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ggplot2))

  fit_twfe <- lm(Y ~ D + factor(id) + factor(t), data = did_stag)
  tau_twfe <- coef(fit_twfe)[["D"]]

  did_2x2 <- function(df, g_treat, g_ctrl, pre_t, post_t) {
    yt_pre <- mean(df$Y[df$group == g_treat & df$t %in% pre_t])
    yt_post <- mean(df$Y[df$group == g_treat & df$t %in% post_t])
    yc_pre <- mean(df$Y[df$group == g_ctrl & df$t %in% pre_t])
    yc_post <- mean(df$Y[df$group == g_ctrl & df$t %in% post_t])
    (yt_post - yt_pre) - (yc_post - yc_pre)
  }

  g_vals <- sort(unique(did_stag$G[is.finite(did_stag$G)]))
  g_early <- g_vals[1]
  g_late <- g_vals[2]
  t_vals <- sort(unique(did_stag$t))

  est_e_never <- did_2x2(did_stag, "early", "never", pre_t = t_vals[t_vals < g_early], post_t = t_vals[t_vals >= g_early])
  est_l_never <- did_2x2(did_stag, "late", "never", pre_t = t_vals[t_vals < g_late], post_t = t_vals[t_vals >= g_late])

  est_e_l_notyet <- did_2x2(
    did_stag,
    "early", "late",
    pre_t = t_vals[t_vals < g_early],
    post_t = t_vals[t_vals >= g_early & t_vals < g_late]
  )

  est_l_e_already <- did_2x2(
    did_stag,
    "late", "early",
    pre_t = t_vals[t_vals >= g_early & t_vals < g_late],
    post_t = t_vals[t_vals >= g_late]
  )

  df_comp <- data.frame(
    comparison = c(
      "Early vs never (clean control)",
      "Late vs never (clean control)",
      "Early vs late (late not yet treated)",
      "Late vs early (early already treated)"
    ),
    est = c(est_e_never, est_l_never, est_e_l_notyet, est_l_e_already),
    type = c("clean", "clean", "not_yet", "already_treated")
  )

  df_comp$type <- factor(df_comp$type, levels = c("clean", "not_yet", "already_treated"))
  df_comp$comparison <- factor(df_comp$comparison, levels = rev(df_comp$comparison))

  ggplot(df_comp, aes(x = comparison, y = est, fill = type)) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linewidth = 0.4, color = "gray35") +
    geom_hline(yintercept = tau_twfe, linewidth = 0.8, linetype = 3, color = "gray25") +
    geom_col(width = 0.75) +
    coord_flip() +
    scale_fill_manual(
      values = c(clean = "gray70", not_yet = "steelblue3", already_treated = "firebrick"),
      breaks = c("clean", "not_yet", "already_treated"),
      labels = c("Clean control", "Not-yet-treated control", "Already-treated control"),
      name = "Comparison type"
    ) +
    labs(
      x = NULL,
      y = "2x2 DiD estimate",
      title = "Different 2x2 comparisons can differ; TWFE (dashed) averages them implicitly"
    ) +
    theme_classic(base_size = 12) +
    theme(legend.position = "bottom")
@
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}[fragile]{Toy staggered adoption: TWFE vs.\ transparent targets}
\small
In a simple staggered-adoption toy model with heterogeneous effects, TWFE can differ from a transparent "average of cohort-time effects." \pause

<<did-stag-twfe-vs-att, echo=FALSE, fig=TRUE, height=3.4, width=7.6>>=
  suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ggplot2))

  # TWFE estimate
  fit_twfe <- lm(Y ~ D + factor(id) + factor(t), data = did_stag)
  tau_twfe <- coef(fit_twfe)[["D"]]

  # True event-time effects (by construction)
  true_k <- aggregate(te_true ~ event_time, data = subset(did_stag, D == 1), FUN = mean)
  names(true_k) <- c("k", "true_tau")

  # "CS-style" group-time ATT using not-yet-treated + never-treated as controls, baseline at g-1.
  treated_groups <- sort(unique(did_stag$G[is.finite(did_stag$G)]))
  att_gt <- do.call(rbind, lapply(treated_groups, function(g) {
    out <- do.call(rbind, lapply(sort(unique(did_stag$t[did_stag$t >= g])), function(tt) {
      base_t <- g - 1
      treat_idx_t <- did_stag$G == g & did_stag$t == tt
      treat_idx_b <- did_stag$G == g & did_stag$t == base_t

      ctrl_idx_t <- (did_stag$G > tt) & did_stag$t == tt
      ctrl_idx_b <- (did_stag$G > tt) & did_stag$t == base_t

      att <- (mean(did_stag$Y[treat_idx_t]) - mean(did_stag$Y[treat_idx_b])) -
        (mean(did_stag$Y[ctrl_idx_t]) - mean(did_stag$Y[ctrl_idx_b]))

      data.frame(g = g, t = tt, k = tt - g, att = att)
    }))
    out
  }))

  # Aggregate across cohorts at each event time with weights proportional to cohort size
  n_by_g <- aggregate(id ~ G, data = subset(did_stag, is.finite(G)), FUN = function(x) length(unique(x)))
  names(n_by_g) <- c("g", "n_g")
  att_gt <- merge(att_gt, n_by_g, by = "g", all.x = TRUE)

  att_k <- aggregate(att ~ k, data = att_gt, FUN = function(x) NA_real_)
  att_k$att <- sapply(att_k$k, function(k) {
    tmp <- subset(att_gt, k == k)
    sum(tmp$att * tmp$n_g) / sum(tmp$n_g)
  })

  df_plot <- merge(true_k, att_k, by = "k", all = TRUE)

  ggplot(df_plot, aes(x = k)) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = tau_twfe, linewidth = 0.8, linetype = 3, color = "gray30") +
    geom_line(aes(y = true_tau), linewidth = 1.0, color = "firebrick") +
    geom_point(aes(y = true_tau), size = 1.7, color = "firebrick") +
    geom_line(aes(y = att), linewidth = 1.0, color = "navy") +
    geom_point(aes(y = att), size = 1.7, color = "navy") +
    labs(
      x = "Event time k",
      y = "Effect",
      title = "Event-time effects: true (red) vs CS-style ATT aggregation (blue), TWFE (dashed)"
    ) +
    theme_classic(base_size = 12)
@

\vspace{0.25em}
\scriptsize
Toy message: when effects differ by cohort/event time, define the estimand first (e.g., \(ATT(g,t)\) or event-time averages), then use an estimator that targets it.
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Modern targets: group-time effects}
\small
One clean estimand with staggered adoption is the group-time ATT:\pause
\[
ATT(g,t)\equiv \E\!\left[Y_{it}(1)-Y_{it}(0)\mid G_i=g\right],
\qquad t\ge g,
\]
where \(G_i\) is the first-treated time for unit \(i\).\pause

\vspace{0.25em}
Modern estimators (e.g., Callaway--Sant'Anna) build event-study plots by aggregating \(ATT(g,t)\) across cohorts with transparent weights.
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Callaway--Sant'Anna: comparison sets and aggregation}
\small
For each treated cohort \(g\) and time \(t\ge g\), define a \textbf{control set} \(C_{g,t}\):\pause
\begin{wideitemize}
\item \textbf{Never-treated controls:} units that are never treated.\pause
\item \textbf{Not-yet-treated controls:} units with \(G_i>t\) (untreated by time \(t\)).\pause
\end{wideitemize}

\vspace{0.25em}
One (simplified) way to think about \(ATT(g,t)\) is a 2x2 DiD within cohort \(g\), using baseline \(g-1\):\pause
\[
ATT(g,t)\approx
\Big(\E[Y_t-Y_{g-1}\mid G=g]\Big)
-\Big(\E[Y_t-Y_{g-1}\mid i\in C_{g,t}]\Big).
\]

\vspace{0.25em}
\pause
\textbf{Aggregation:} to plot event time \(k=t-g\), average \(ATT(g,g+k)\) across cohorts \(g\) using transparent weights (often proportional to cohort size or share treated at that event time).
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Modern workflow (high level)}
\small
With staggered adoption, a useful workflow is:\pause
\begin{enumerate}
\item Define the estimand: \(ATT(g,t)\) (or event-time effects) for clear \(g,t\).\pause
\item Choose a comparison group: never-treated or not-yet-treated units.\pause
\item Estimate \(ATT(g,t)\) within each cohort-time cell.\pause
\item Aggregate to event time \(k=t-g\) with transparent weights; plot leads/lags.\pause
\item Do robustness checks (windows, alternative controls, placebo outcomes).\pause
\end{enumerate}

\vspace{0.25em}
\scriptsize
Callaway--Sant'Anna (2021) and Sun--Abraham (2021) are standard references for modern practice.
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Synthetic control (SC): when DiD is too thin}
\small
When there is a single treated unit (or a small number) and a long time series, DiD with one comparison unit can be fragile.\pause

\begin{wideitemize}
\item Synthetic control constructs a weighted combination of control units to match the treated unit's pre-treatment outcomes.\pause
\item Then it uses that weighted combination as the counterfactual post-treatment trend.\pause
\end{wideitemize}

\vspace{0.25em}
\scriptsize
Core references: Abadie \& Gardeazabal (2003), Abadie, Diamond \& Hainmueller (2010).
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{SC vs.\ DiD (conceptual link)}
\small
\begin{wideitemize}
\item Both are about constructing a credible counterfactual trend.\pause
\item DiD: a comparison group + a parallel-trends assumption.\pause
\item SC: a data-driven comparison group (weights) chosen to match the pre-period.\pause
\end{wideitemize}

\vspace{0.25em}
\textbf{Tradeoff:} SC can improve pre-period fit, but it does not eliminate the need for a design argument (and it is still local/design-dependent).
\end{frame}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------%
\begin{frame}{Week 8 summary (RD + DiD)}
\small
\begin{wideitemize}
\item RD: under continuity at the cutoff, the jump in \(\E[Y\mid X=x]\) identifies \(\E[Y(1)-Y(0)\mid X=c]\) (local effect).\pause
\item DiD: under parallel trends, the difference in average changes identifies a causal effect for the treated group.\pause
\item With panels: inference is hard (serial correlation); cluster appropriately.\pause
\item With staggered adoption: define the estimand first; don't default to TWFE.\pause
\end{wideitemize}
\end{frame}

